# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: memory-protection-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:memory-protection-unit/arm-cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A **memory management unit** (**MMU**), sometimes called **paged memory management unit** (**PMMU**), is a computer hardware unit that examines all references to memory, and translates the memory addresses being referenced, known as virtual memory addresses, into physical addresses in main memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In modern systems, programs generally have addresses that access the theoretical maximum memory of the computer architecture, 32 or 64 bits.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU maps the addresses from each program into separate areas in physical memory, which is generally much smaller than the theoretical maximum.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This is possible because programs rarely use large amounts of memory at any one time.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Most modern operating systems (OS) work in concert with an MMU to provide virtual memory (VM) support.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU tracks memory use in fixed-size blocks known as *pages*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If a program refers to a location in a page that is not in physical memory, the MMU sends an interrupt to the operating system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OS selects a lesser-used block in memory, writes it to backing storage such as a hard drive if it has been modified since it was read in, reads the page from backing storage into that block, and sets up the MMU to map the block to the originally requested page so the program can use it.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some simpler real-time operating systems do not support virtual memory and do not need an MMU, but still need a hardware memory protection unit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] MMUs generally provide memory protection to block attempts by a program to access memory it has not previously requested, which prevents a misbehaving or malicious program from modifying or reading data belonging to another program.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Later microprocessors (such as the Motorola 68030 and the Zilog Z280) placed the MMU together with the CPU on the same integrated circuit, as did the Intel 80286 and later x86 microprocessors.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some early systems, especially 8-bit systems, used very simple MMUs to perform bank switching.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Early systems used base and bounds addressing that further developed into segmentation, or used a fixed set of blocks instead of loading them on demand.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The difference between these two approaches is the size of the contiguous block of memory; paged systems break up main memory into a series of equal-sized blocks, while segmented systems generally allow for variable sizes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In segmented translation, a memory address contains a segment number and an offset within the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Segments are variable-length and may have permissions, such as read, write, and execute, associated with them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A segment is loaded into a contiguous area of physical memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Typically, the segment number is used as an index into a *segment table*; each entry in the segment table holds the address of the area of physical memory, the length of the segment, and other information such as permission flags.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This style has the advantage of simplicity; the memory blocks are continuous, and thus only the two values, base and limit, need to be stored for mapping purposes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The disadvantage of this approach is that it leads to an effect known as *external fragmentation*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This occurs when memory allocations are released but are non-contiguous.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In this case, enough memory may be available to handle a request, but this is spread out and cannot be allocated to a single segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some models of the PDP-11 16-bit minicomputer have a segmented memory management unit with a set of *page address registers* (PARs) and *page description registers* (PDRs); this maps a 16-bit virtual address to an 18-bit physical address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The PDP-11/70 expands that to produce a 22-bit physical address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Segmenting was widely used on microcomputer platforms of the 1980s.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Among the MMUs that used this concept were the Motorola 68451 and the Zilog Z8010, but many other examples exist.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Intel 8086, Intel 8088, Intel 80186, and Intel 80188 provide crude memory segmentation and no memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] (Every byte of every segment is always available to any program.) The 16-bit segment registers allow for 65,536 segments; each segment begins at a fixed offset equal to 16 times the segment number; the segment starting address granularity is 16 bytes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each segment grants read-write access to 64 KiB (65,536 bytes) of address space (this limit is set by the 16-bit PC and SP registers; the processor does no bounds checking).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Offset+address exceeding 0xFFFFF wraps around to 0x00000.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each 64 KiB segment overlaps the next 4,095 segments; each physical address can be denoted by 4,096 segment–offset pairs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This scheme can address only 1 MiB (1024 KiB) of physical memory (and memory-mapped i/o).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] (Optional expanded memory hardware can add bank-switched memory under software control.) Later x86 processors, starting with the Intel 80286, supported real segmented mapping, with a segment table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In paged translation, the address space (the range of addresses used by the processor) is divided into pages, each having a size which is a power of 2, usually a few kilobytes, but they may be much larger.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Programs reference memory using the natural address size of the machine, typically 32 or 64 bits in modern systems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The bottom bits of the address (the offset within a page) are left unchanged.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The upper address bits are the virtual page numbers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Most MMUs use an in-memory table of items called a page table, containing one page table entry (PTE) per virtual page, to map virtual page numbers to physical page numbers in main memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Multi-level page tables are often used to reduce the size of the page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] An associative cache of PTEs is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB) and is used to avoid the necessity of accessing the main memory every time a virtual address is mapped.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Other MMUs may have a private array of memory, a set of registers, or a one-or-more-level array of static RAM to store a set of mapping information.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU splits the virtual address into a virtual page number and an offset within the page.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The virtual page number is used to select a page table entry; if the page table entry is found, and the page is marked as being in memory, the physical page number in the page table entry is combined with the offset to construct the physical address corresponding to the virtual address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] One issue with paged translation is that as the virtual address space expands, the amount of memory needed to hold the mapping increases as well.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] For instance, in the 68020 the addresses are 32 bits wide, meaning the virtual page number for an 8 kB page size is the upper 19 bits of the address, and a single-level page table would be 512 kB in size.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In the 1980s, for an in-memory page table, this might be a significant fraction of the main memory of the machine, and, for an MMU that holds the page map in static RAM, might require a costly amount of static RAM.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This problem can be reduced by making the pages larger, say 64 kB instead of 8.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Now the page index uses 16 bits and the resulting page table is 64 kB, which is more tractable.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Moving to a larger page size leads to the second problem: increased internal fragmentation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A program that generates a series of requests for small blocks will be assigned large blocks and thereby waste large amounts of memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If the address space is sparse, so that not all regions of it are allocated, the problem can be reduced by using a multi-level page table or static RAM map, and not allocate all the page table entries that would be needed for an empty region.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The paged translation approach was widely used by microprocessor MMUs in the 1970s and 1980s, including the 68020's 68851 and the on-chip MMU of the 68030, the Zilog Z8000's Z8015, and the NS32000 series's NS16082.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Sometimes, a page table entry or other per-page information prohibits access to a particular virtual page, perhaps because no physical random-access memory (RAM) has been allocated to that virtual page.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In this case, the MMU signals a page fault to the CPU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The operating system (OS) then handles the situation, perhaps by trying to find a spare frame of RAM and set up the page map to map it to the requested virtual address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If no RAM is free, it may be necessary to choose an existing page (known as a *victim*), using some replacement algorithm, and save it to disk (a process called *paging*).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] With some MMUs, there can also be a shortage of PTEs, in which case the OS will have to free one for the new mapping.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU may also generate illegal access error conditions or invalid page faults upon illegal or non-existing memory accesses, respectively, leading to segmentation fault or bus error conditions when handled by the operating system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Paged translation mitigates the problem of external fragmentation of memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] After blocks of memory have been allocated and freed, the free memory may become fragmented (discontinuous) so that the largest contiguous block of free memory may be much smaller than the total amount.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] With virtual memory, a contiguous range of virtual addresses can be mapped to several non-contiguous blocks of physical memory; this non-contiguous allocation is one of the benefits of paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] However, paged translation causes another problem, *internal fragmentation*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This occurs when a program requests a block of memory that does not cleanly map into a page, for instance, if a program requests a 1 KB buffer to perform file work.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In this case, the request results in an entire page being set aside even though only 1 KB of the page will ever be used; if pages are larger than 1 KB, the remainder of the page is wasted.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If many small allocations of this sort are made, memory can be used up even though much of it remains empty.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some systems, such as the GE 645 and its successors, used both segmentation and paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The table of segments, instead of containing per-segment entries giving the physical base address and length of the segment, contains entries giving the physical base address of a page table for the segment, in addition to the length of the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Physical memory is divided into fixed-size pages, and the same techniques used for purely page-based demand paging are used for segment-and-page-based demand paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Signetics 68905 MMU, designed for the Motorola 68000, 68010, and 68012 microprocessors, supported segmentation and paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Both Signetics and Philips produced a version of the 68000 that combined the 68905 on the same physical chip as the processor, the 68070.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] An MMU can provide memory protection, so that attempts by code to access or modify data to which it does not have access result in a failure; this catches both software bugs and deliberate attempts to access or modify that data.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Typically, an operating system assigns each program its own virtual address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] An MMU can also be used to expand the size of the physical address when the virtual address is too small.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] For instance, the PDP-11 originally had a 16-bit address that made it too small as memory sizes increased in the 1970s.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This was addressed by expanding the physical memory bus to 18 bits, and using an MMU to add two more bits based on other pins on the processor bus to indicate which program was accessing memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some MMUs, such as the Signetics 68905, also included a controller to manage a processor cache, which stores recently accessed data in a very fast memory and thus reduces the need to talk to the slower main memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In some implementations, MMUs are also responsible for bus arbitration, controlling access to the memory bus among the many parts of the computer that desire access.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Hardware that performs direct memory access completely bypasses the CPU's MMU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some I/O systems allow DMA hardware to use physical addresses to read or write directly anywhere in physical RAM without any restrictions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Other I/O systems have a separate MMU called an input-output memory management unit (IOMMU) that can be programmed by the OS to translate device addresses from the DMA hardware to specific, limited physical pages chosen by the OS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The IOMMU can be used to block DMA attacks.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Most modern systems divide memory into pages that are 4–64 KB in size, often with the capability to use so-called huge pages of 2 MB or 1 GB in size (often both variants are possible).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Page translations are cached in a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some systems, mainly older RISC designs, trap into the OS when a page translation is not found in the TLB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Most systems use a hardware-based tree walker.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Most systems allow the MMU to be disabled, but some disable the MMU when trapping into OS code.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The IBM System/360 Model 67, which was introduced August, 1965, included an MMU called a dynamic address translation (DAT) box.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] It has the unusual feature of storing accessed and dirty bits outside of the page table (along with the four bit protection key for all S/360 processors).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] They refer to physical memory rather than virtual memory, and are accessed by special-purpose instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This reduces overhead for the OS, which would otherwise need to propagate accessed and dirty bits from the page tables to a more physically oriented data structure.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This makes OS-level virtualization, later called paravirtualization, easier.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Starting in August, 1972, the IBM System/370 has a similar MMU, although it initially supported only a 24-bit virtual address space rather than the 32-bit virtual address space of the System/360 Model 67.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] It also stores the accessed and dirty bits outside the page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In early 1983, the System/370-XA architecture expanded the virtual address space to 31 bits, and in 2000, the 64-bit z/Architecture was introduced, with the address space expanded to 64 bits; those continue to store the accessed and dirty bits outside the page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] VAX pages are 512 bytes, which is very small.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] An OS may treat multiple pages as if they were a single larger page.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] For example, Linux on VAX groups eight pages together.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Thus, the system is viewed as having 4 KB pages.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The VAX divides memory into four fixed-purpose regions, each 1 GB in size.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Used for general-purpose per-process memory such as heaps.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] and other per-process control structures managed by the operating system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] (Or system space) which is global to all processes and stores operating system code and data, whether paged or not, including pagetables.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Normally, this would be very wasteful when addresses are used at both ends of the possible range, but the page tables for P0 and P1 space are stored in the paged S0 space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Thus, there is effectively a two-level tree, allowing applications to have a sparse memory layout without wasting a lot of space on unused page table entries.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Unlike page table entries in most MMUs, page table entries in the VAX MMU lack an accessed bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] OSes which implement paging must find some way to emulate the accessed bit if they are to operate efficiently.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Typically, the OS will periodically unmap pages so that page-not-present faults can be used to let the OS set an accessed bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] ARM architecture-based application processors implement an MMU defined by ARM's virtual memory system architecture (VMSA).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The current architecture defines PTEs for describing 4 KB and 64 KB pages, 1 MB sections and 16 MB super-sections; legacy versions also defined a 1 KB tiny page.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] ARM uses a two-level page table if using 4 KB and 64 KB pages, or just a one-level page table for 1 MB sections and 16 MB sections.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] TLB updates are performed automatically by page table walking hardware.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] PTEs include read/write access permission based on privilege, cacheability information, an NX bit, and a non-secure bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] DEC Alpha processors divide memory into 8 KB, 16 KB, 32 KB, or 64 KB; the page size is dependent on the processor. pages.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] After a TLB miss, low-level firmware machine code (here called PALcode) walks a page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OpenVMS AXP PALcode and DEC OSF/1 PALcode walk a three-level tree-structured page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The sizes of the fields are dependent on the page size; all three tree index fields are the same size.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OpenVMS AXP PALcode supports full read and write permission bits for user, supervisor, executive, and kernel modes, and also supports fault on read/write/execute bits are also supported.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The DEC OSF/1 PALcode supports full read and write permission bits for user and kernel modes, and also supports fault on read/write/execute bits.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Windows NT AXP PALcode can either walk a single-level page table in a virtual address space or a two-level page table in physical address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The upper 32 bits of an address are ignored.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] For a single-level page table, addresses are broken down into a set of bits to index the page table and remaining bits that pass through to the physical address without modification, indexing a byte within the page.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The sizes of the fields are dependent on the page size.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Windows NT AXP PALcode supports a page being accessible only from kernel mode or being accessible from user and kernel mode, and also supports a fault on write bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MIPS architecture supports one to 64 entries in the TLB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The number of TLB entries is configurable at CPU configuration before synthesis.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each TLB entry maps a virtual page number (VPN2) to either one of two page frame numbers (PFN0 or PFN1), depending on the least significant bit of the virtual address that is not part of the page mask.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This bit and the page mask bits are not stored in the VPN2.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each TLB entry has its own page size, which can be any value from 1 KB to 256 MB in multiples of four.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each PFN in a TLB entry has a caching attribute, a dirty and a valid status bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A VPN2 has a global status bit and an OS assigned ID, which participates in the virtual address TLB entry match if the global status bit is set to zero.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A PFN stores the physical address without the page mask bits.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A TLB refill exception is generated when there are no entries in the TLB that match the mapped virtual address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A TLB invalid exception is generated when there is a match, but the entry is marked invalid.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A TLB modified exception is generated when a store instruction references a mapped address and the matching entry's dirty status is not set.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If a TLB exception occurs when processing a TLB exception, a double-fault TLB exception, it is dispatched to its own exception handler.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] MIPS32 and MIPS32r2 support 32 bits of virtual address space and up to 36 bits of physical address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] MIPS64 supports up to 64 bits of virtual address space and up to 59 bits of physical address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The original Sun-1 is a single-board computer built around the Motorola 68000 microprocessor and introduced in 1982.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] It includes the original Sun 1 memory management unit that provides address translation, memory protection, memory sharing and memory allocation for multiple processes running on the CPU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] All access of the CPU to private on-board RAM, external Multibus memory, on-board I/O and the Multibus I/O runs through the MMU, where address translation and protection are done in a uniform fashion.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU is implemented in hardware on the CPU board.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MMU consists of a context register, a segment map and a page map.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Virtual addresses from the CPU are translated into intermediate addresses by the segment map, which in turn are translated into physical addresses by the page map.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The page size is 2 KB and the segment size is 32 KB which gives 16 pages per segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Up to 16 contexts can be mapped concurrently.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The maximum logical address space for a context is 1024 pages or 2 MB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The maximum physical address that can be mapped simultaneously is also 2 MB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The context register is important in a multitasking operating system because it allows the CPU to switch between processes without reloading all the translation state information.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The 4-bit context register can switch between 16 sections of the segment map under supervisor control, which allows 16 contexts to be mapped concurrently.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Each context has its own virtual address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Sharing of virtual address space and inter-context communications can be provided by writing the same values into the segment or page maps of different contexts.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Additional contexts can be handled by treating the segment map as a context cache and replacing out-of-date contexts on a least-recently used basis.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The context register makes no distinction between user and supervisor states.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Interrupts and traps do not switch contexts, which requires that all valid interrupt vectors always be mapped in page 0 of context, as well as the valid supervisor stack.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Sun-2 workstations are similar; they are built around the Motorola 68010 microprocessor and have a similar memory management unit, with 2 KB pages and 32 KB segments.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The context register has a 3-bit system context used in supervisor state and a 3-bit user context used in user state.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Sun-3 workstations, except for the Sun-3/80, Sun-3/460, Sun-3/470, and Sun-3/480, are built around the Motorola 68020, and have a similar memory management unit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Sun-4 workstations are built around various SPARC microprocessors, and have a memory management unit similar to that of the Sun-3 workstations.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In PowerPC G1, G2, G3, and G4 pages are normally 4 KB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] After a TLB miss, the standard PowerPC MMU begins two simultaneous lookups.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] One lookup attempts to match the address with one of four or eight data block address translation (DBAT) registers, or four or eight instruction block address translation registers (IBAT), as appropriate.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The BAT registers can map linear chunks of memory as large as 256 MB, and are normally used by an OS to map large portions of the address space for the OS kernel's own use.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If the BAT lookup succeeds, the other lookup is halted and ignored.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The other lookup, not directly supported by all processors in this family, is via a so-called inverted page table, which acts as a hashed off-chip extension of the TLB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] First, the top four bits of the address are used to select one of 16 segment registers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Then 24 bits from the segment register replace those four bits, producing a 52-bit address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The use of segment registers allows multiple processes to share the same hash table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The 52-bit address is hashed, then used as an index into the off-chip table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] There, a group of eight-page table entries is scanned for one that matches.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If none match due to excessive hash collisions, the processor tries again with a slightly different hash function.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If this, too, fails, the CPU traps into OS (with MMU disabled) so that the problem may be resolved.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OS needs to discard an entry from the hash table to make space for a new entry.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OS may generate the new entry from a more normal tree-like page table or from per-mapping data structures, which are likely to be slower and more space-efficient.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Support for no-execute control is in the segment registers, leading to 256 MB granularity.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A major problem with this design is poor cache locality caused by the hash function.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Tree-based designs avoid this by placing the page table entries for adjacent pages in adjacent locations.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] An operating system running on the PowerPC may minimize the size of the hash table to reduce this problem.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] It is also somewhat slow to remove the page table entries of a process.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The OS may avoid reusing segment values to delay facing this, or it may elect to suffer the waste of memory associated with per-process hash tables.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] G1 chips do not search for page table entries, but they do generate the hash, with the expectation that an OS will search the standard hash table via software.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] G2, G3, and early G4 chips use hardware to search the hash table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The latest chips allow the OS to choose either method.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] On chips that make this optional or do not support it at all, the OS may choose to use a tree-based page table exclusively.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The x86 architecture has evolved over a very long time while maintaining full software compatibility, even for OS code.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Thus, the MMU is extremely complex, with many different possible operating modes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The 8086/8088 and 80186/80188 have no memory management unit; they support segmentation, but only to support more physical memory than a 16-bit address can support, as the segment number, in a segment register, is multiplied by 16 and added to the segment offset to generate a physical address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The 80286 added an MMU that supports segmentation, but not paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The 80386, which introduced the 32-bit IA-32 version of x86, and subsequent x86 CPUs, support segmentation and paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The result may be looked up via a tree-structured page table, with the bits of the address being split as follows: 10 bits for the branch of the tree, 10 bits for the leaves of the branch, and the 12 lowest bits being directly copied to the result.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Segment registers, used in pre-80386 CPUs to extend the address space, are not used in modern OSes, with one major exception: access to thread-specific data for applications or CPU-specific data for OS kernels, which is done with explicit use of the FS and GS segment registers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] All memory access involves a segment register, chosen according to the code being executed.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Except when using FS or GS, the OS ensures that the offset will be zero.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some operating systems, such as OpenBSD with its W^X feature, and Linux with the Exec Shield or PaX patches, may also limit the length of the code segment, as specified by the CS register, to disallow execution of code in modifiable regions of the address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Minor revisions of the MMU introduced with the Pentium have allowed very large 4 MB pages by skipping the bottom level of the tree (this leaves 10 bits for indexing the first level of page hierarchy with the remaining 10+12 bits being directly copied to the result).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Minor revisions of the MMU introduced with the Pentium Pro introduced the physical address extension (PAE) feature, enabling 36-bit physical addresses with 2+9+9 bits for three-level page tables and 12 lowest bits being directly copied to the result.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Large pages (2 MB) are also available by skipping the bottom level of the tree (resulting in 2+9 bits for a two-level table hierarchy and the remaining 9+12 lowest bits copied directly).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In addition, the page attribute table allowed specification of cacheability by looking up a few high bits in a small on-CPU table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] No-execute support was originally only provided on a per-segment basis, making it very awkward to use.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] More recent x86 chips provide a per-page NX bit (no-execute bit) in the PAE mode.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The W^X, Exec Shield, and PaX mechanisms described above emulate per-page non-execute support on machines with x86 processors that lack the NX bit by setting the length of the code segment, with a performance loss and a reduction in the available address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] x86-64, the 64-bit version of the x86 architecture, almost entirely removes segmentation in favor of the flat memory model used by almost all operating systems for the 386 or newer processors.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In long mode, all segment offsets are ignored, except for the FS and GS segments; linear addresses are 64-bit rather than 32-bit, with the lowest 48 bits of the address being significant.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] When used with 4 KB pages, the page table tree has four levels instead of three, to handle the larger linear addresses; in some newer x86-64 processors, a fifth page table level can be enabled, to support 57-bit linear addresses.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In all levels of the page table, the page table entry includes an NX bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] 48-bit linear addresses are divided as follows: 16 bits unused, nine bits each for four tree levels (for a total of 36 bits), and the 12 lowest bits directly copied to the result.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] With 2 MB pages, there are only three levels of page table, for a total of 27 bits used in paging and 21 bits of offset.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Some newer CPUs also support a 1 GB page with two levels of paging and 30 bits of offset.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] CPUID can be used to determine if 1 GB pages are supported.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In all three cases, the 16 highest bits are required to be equal to the 48th bit, or in other words, the low 48 bits are sign extended to the higher bits.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This is done to allow further expansion of the addressable range, without compromising backwards compatibility.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] 57-bit linear addresses are divided as follows: 7 bits unused, nine bits each for five tree levels (for a total of 45 bits), and the 12 lowest bits directly copied to the result.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Burroughs B5000 from 1961 was the first commercial system to support virtual memory (after the Atlas), has no need for an external MMU.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The B5000 and its successors up to current Unisys ClearPath MCP (Libra) systems provide the two functions of an MMU — virtual memory addresses and memory protection — with a different architectural approach.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] First, in the mapping of virtual memory addresses, instead of needing an MMU, the machines are descriptor-based.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The uppermost bit of a 48-bit memory word in the Burroughs B5000 series systems indicate whether the word is a user data or a descriptor/control word; descriptors were read-only to user processes and could only be updated by the system (hardware or operating system).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Memory words in the B6x00/B7x00/B5900/A-series/Unisys MCP systems have 48 data bits and 3 tag bits (and later systems to current have 4 tag bits).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Words whose tag is an odd number are read-only to user processes – descriptors have a tag of 5 and code words have a tag of 3.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] All references to code and data are made using a descriptor.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] When a request is made to access the block for reading or writing, the hardware checks its presence via the presence bit (pbit) in the descriptor.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A pbit of 1 indicates the presence of the block.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] In this case, the block can be accessed via the physical main-memory address in the descriptor.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If the pbit is zero, a pbit interrupt is generated for the MCP (operating system) to make the block present.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If the address field is zero, this is the first access to this block, and it is allocated (an init (initial) pbit).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] If the address field is non-zero, it is a disk address of the block, which has previously been rolled out — the block is fetched from disk, the pbit is set to one and the physical memory address updated to point to the block in memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This makes descriptors equivalent to a page-table entry in an MMU system, but descriptors are free of a table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] All memory allocation is therefore completely automatic (one of the features of modern systems) and there is no way to allocate blocks other than this mechanism.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] There are no such calls as malloc or dealloc, since memory blocks are also automatically allocated on pbit interrupt or discarded.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The scheme is also lazy, since a block will not be allocated until it is actually referenced.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Another way these systems provide a function of an MMU is in protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Since all accesses are via the descriptor, the hardware can check that all accesses are within bounds and, in the case of a write, that the process has write permission.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The MCP system is inherently secure and thus has no need of an MMU to provide this level of memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Blocks can be shared between processes via copy descriptors in process stacks (a stack is a special system structure representing the execution state of a process).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Thus, some processes may have write permission, whereas others do not.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Code segments are read-only, thus reentrant and shared between processes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Copy descriptors contain a 20-bit address field giving the index of the master descriptor in the master descriptor array.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This also implements a very efficient and secure Interprocess Communication (IPC) mechanism.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Blocks can easily be relocated, since only the master descriptor needs to be updated when a block's status changes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Another aspect is performance – do MMU-based or non-MMU-based systems provide better performance?
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] MCP systems may be implemented on top of standard hardware that has an MMU (for example, a standard PC).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] Even if the system implementation uses the MMU in some way, this will not be at all visible at the MCP level.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] A simple technique called bank switching was widely used by early 8-bit microprocessors like the MOS 6502.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] For instance, the Atari MMU would express additional bits on the address bus to select among several *banks* of DRAM memory based on which of the chips was currently active, normally the CPU or ANTIC.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] This was used to expand the available memory on the Atari 130XE to 128 kB.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-management-unit] The Commodore 128 used a similar approach.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] A **memory protection unit** (**MPU**) is a computer hardware unit that provides memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] It is usually implemented as part of the central processing unit (CPU).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] MPU is a trimmed down version of memory management unit (MMU) providing only memory protection support.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] It is usually implemented in low power processors that require only memory protection and do not need the full-fledged feature of a MMU like virtual memory management.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] The MPU allows the privileged software to define memory regions and assign memory access permission and memory attributes to each of them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] Depending on the implementation of the processor, the number of supported memory regions will vary.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] The MPU on ARMv8-M processors supports up to 16 regions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] The memory attributes define the ordering and merging behaviors of these regions, as well as caching and buffering attributes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] Cache attributes can be used by internal caches, if available, and can be exported for use by system caches.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] MPU monitors transactions, including instruction fetches and data accesses from the processor, which can trigger a fault exception when an access violation is detected.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] The main purpose of memory protection is to prevent a process from accessing memory that has not been allocated to it.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection-unit] This prevents a bug or malware within a process from affecting other processes, or the operating system itself.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Segmentation refers to dividing a computer's memory into segments.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A reference to a memory location includes a value that identifies a segment and an offset within that segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A segment descriptor may limit access rights, e.g., read only, only from certain rings.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The x86 architecture has multiple segmentation features, which are helpful for using protected memory on this architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On the x86 architecture, the Global Descriptor Table and Local Descriptor Tables can be used to reference segments in the computer's memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Pointers to memory segments on x86 processors can also be stored in the processor's segment registers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Initially x86 processors had 4 segment registers, CS (code segment), SS (stack segment), DS (data segment) and ES (extra segment); later another two segment registers were added – FS and GS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] In paging the memory address space or segment is divided into equal-sized blocks called pages.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Using virtual memory hardware, each page can reside in any location at a suitable boundary of the computer's physical memory, or be flagged as being protected.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Virtual memory makes it possible to have a linear virtual memory address space and to use it to access blocks fragmented over physical memory address space.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Most computer architectures which support paging also use pages as the basis for memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A *page table* maps virtual memory to physical memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] There may be a single page table, a page table for each process, a page table for each segment, or a hierarchy of page tables, depending on the architecture and the OS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The page tables are usually invisible to the process.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Page tables make it easier to allocate additional memory, as each new page can be allocated from anywhere in physical memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On some systems a page table entry can also designate a page as read-only.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Some operating systems set up a different address space for each process, which provides hard memory protection boundaries.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] It is impossible for an unprivileged application to access a page that has not been explicitly allocated to it, because every memory address either points to a page allocated to that application, or generates an interrupt called a *page fault*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Unallocated pages, and pages allocated to any other application, do not have any addresses from the application point of view.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A page fault may not necessarily indicate an error.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Page faults are not only used for memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The operating system may manage the page table in such a way that a reference to a page that has been previously paged out to secondary storage causes a page fault.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The operating system intercepts the page fault, loads the required memory page, and the application continues as if no fault had occurred.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] This scheme, a type of virtual memory, allows in-memory data not currently in use to be moved to secondary storage and back in a way which is transparent to applications, to increase overall memory capacity.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On some systems, a request for virtual storage may allocate a block of virtual addresses for which no page frames have been assigned, and the system will only assign and initialize page frames when page faults occur.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On some systems a guard page may be used, either for error detection or to automatically grow data structures.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On some systems, the page fault mechanism is also used for executable-space protection such as W^X.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A memory protection key (MPK) mechanism divides physical memory into blocks of a particular size (e.g., 4 KiB), each of which has an associated numerical value called a protection key.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Each process also has a protection key value associated with it.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On a memory access the hardware checks that the current process's protection key matches the value associated with the memory block being accessed; if not, an exception occurs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] This mechanism was introduced in the System/360 architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] It is available on today's System z mainframes and heavily used by System z operating systems and their subsystems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The System/360 protection keys described above are associated with physical addresses.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] This is different from the protection key mechanism used by architectures such as the Hewlett-Packard/Intel IA-64 and Hewlett-Packard PA-RISC, which are associated with virtual addresses, and which allow multiple keys per process.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] In the Itanium and PA-RISC architectures, translations (TLB entries) have *keys* (Itanium) or *access ids* (PA-RISC) associated with them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A running process has several protection key registers (16 for Itanium, 4 for PA-RISC).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A translation selected by the virtual address has its key compared to each of the protection key registers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] If any of them match (plus other possible checks), the access is permitted.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] If none match, a fault or exception is generated.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The software fault handler can, if desired, check the missing key against a larger list of keys maintained by software; thus, the protection key registers inside the processor may be treated as a software-managed cache of a larger list of keys associated with a process.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] PA-RISC has 15–18 bits of key; Itanium mandates at least 18.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Keys are usually associated with *protection domains*, such as libraries, modules, etc.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] In the x86, the protection keys architecture allows tagging virtual addresses for user pages with any of 16 protection keys.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] All the pages tagged with the same protection key constitute a protection domain.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] A new register contains the permissions associated with each of the protection domain.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Load and store operations are checked against both the page table permissions and the protection key permissions associated with the protection domain of the virtual address, and only allowed if both permissions allow the access.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The protection key permissions can be set from user space, allowing applications to directly restrict access to the application data without OS intervention.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Since the protection keys are associated with a virtual address, the protection domains are per address space, so processes running in different address spaces can each use all 16 domains.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] In Multics and systems derived from it, each segment has a protection ring for reading, writing and execution; an attempt by a process with a higher ring number than the ring number for the segment causes a fault.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] There is a mechanism for safely calling procedures that run in a lower ring and returning to the higher ring.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] There are mechanisms for a routine running with a low ring number to access a parameter with the larger of its own ring and the caller's ring.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Simulation is the use of a monitoring program to interpret the machine code instructions of some computer architectures.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Such an instruction set simulator can provide memory protection by using a segmentation-like scheme and validating the target address and length of each instruction in real time before actually executing them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The simulator must calculate the target address and length and compare this against a list of valid address ranges that it holds concerning the thread's environment, such as any dynamic memory blocks acquired since the thread's inception, plus any valid shared static memory slots.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The meaning of "valid" may change throughout the thread's life depending upon context.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] It may sometimes be allowed to alter a static block of storage, and sometimes not, depending upon the current mode of execution, which may or may not depend on a storage key or supervisor state.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] It is generally not advisable to use this method of memory protection where adequate facilities exist on a CPU, as this takes valuable processing power from the computer.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Capability-based addressing is a method of memory protection that is unused in modern commercial computers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] In this method, pointers are replaced by protected objects (called *capabilities*) that can only be created using privileged instructions which may only be executed by the kernel, or some other process authorized to do so.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] This effectively lets the kernel control which processes may access which objects in memory, with no need to use separate address spaces or context switches.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Only a few commercial products used capability based security: Plessey System 250, IBM System/38, Intel iAPX 432 architecture and KeyKOS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Capability approaches are widely used in research systems such as EROS and Combex DARPA browser.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] They are used conceptually as the basis for some virtual machines, most notably Smalltalk and Java.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Currently, the DARPA-funded CHERI project at University of Cambridge is working to create a modern capability machine that also supports legacy software.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Dynamic tainting is a technique for protecting programs from illegal memory accesses.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] When memory is allocated, at runtime, this technique taints both the memory and the corresponding pointer using the same taint mark.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Taint marks are then suitably propagated while the program executes and are checked every time a memory address *m* is accessed through a pointer *p*; if the taint marks associated with *m* and *p* differ, the execution is stopped and the illegal access is reported.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] SPARC M7 processors (and higher) implement dynamic tainting in hardware.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Oracle markets this feature as Silicon Secured Memory (SSM) (previously branded as Application Data Integrity (ADI)).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The lowRISC CPU design includes dynamic tainting under the name Tagged Memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] The protection level of a particular implementation may be measured by how closely it adheres to the principle of minimum privilege.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Different operating systems use different forms of memory protection or separation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] Although memory protection was common on most mainframes and many minicomputer systems from the 1960s, true memory separation was not used in home computer operating systems until OS/2 (and in RISC OS) was released in 1987.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On prior systems, such lack of protection was even used as a form of interprocess communication, by sending a pointer between processes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] It is possible for processes to access System Memory in the Windows 9x family of operating systems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-protection] On Unix-like systems, the `mprotect` system call is used to control memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segments usually correspond to natural divisions of a program such as individual routines or data tables so segmentation is generally more visible to the programmer than paging alone.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segments may be created for program modules, or for classes of memory usage such as code segments and data segments.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Certain segments may be shared between programs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segmentation was originally invented as a method by which system software could isolate software processes (tasks) and data they are using.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] It was intended to increase reliability of the systems running multiple processes simultaneously.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] In a system using segmentation, computer memory addresses consist of a segment id and an offset within the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] A hardware memory management unit (MMU) is responsible for translating the segment and offset into a physical address, and for performing checks to make sure the translation can be done and that the reference to that segment and offset is permitted.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Each segment has a length and set of permissions (for example, *read*, *write*, *execute*) associated with it.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] A process is only allowed to make a reference into a segment if the type of reference is allowed by the permissions, and if the offset within the segment is within the range specified by the length of the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Otherwise, a hardware exception such as a segmentation fault is raised.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segments may also be used to implement virtual memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] In this case each segment has an associated flag indicating whether it is present in main memory or not.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] If a segment is accessed that is not present in main memory, a "segment not present" exception is raised, and the operating system will read the segment into memory from secondary storage.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segmentation is one method of implementing memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Paging is another, and they can be combined.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The size of a memory segment is generally not fixed and may be as small as a single byte.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Segmentation has been implemented several ways on various hardware, with or without paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Intel x86 memory segmentation does not fit either model and is discussed separately below, and also in greater detail in a separate article.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Associated with each segment is information that indicates where the segment is located in memory— the *segment base*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] When a program references a memory location, the offset is added to the segment base to generate a physical memory address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] An implementation of virtual memory on a system using segmentation without paging requires that entire segments be swapped back and forth between main memory and secondary storage.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] When a segment is swapped in, the operating system has to allocate enough contiguous free memory to hold the entire segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Often memory fragmentation results if there is not enough contiguous memory even though there may be enough in total.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Instead of a memory location, the segment information includes the address of a page table for the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] When a program references a memory location the offset is translated to a memory address using the page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] A segment can be extended by allocating another memory page and adding it to the segment's page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] An implementation of virtual memory on a system using segmentation with paging usually only moves individual pages back and forth between main memory and secondary storage, similar to a paged non-segmented system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Pages of the segment can be located anywhere in main memory and need not be contiguous.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] This usually results in a reduced amount of input/output between primary and secondary storage and reduced memory fragmentation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The Burroughs Corporation B5000 computer was one of the first to implement segmentation, and "perhaps the first commercial computer to provide virtual memory" based on segmentation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The B5000 is equipped with a segment information table called the Program Reference Table (PRT) which is used to indicate whether the corresponding segment resides in the main memory, to maintain the base address and the size of the segment.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The later B6500 computer also implemented segmentation; a version of its architecture is still in use today on the Unisys ClearPath Libra servers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The GE 645 computer, a modification of the GE-635 with segmentation and paging support added, was designed in 1964 to support Multics.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The Intel iAPX 432, begun in 1975, attempted to implement a true segmented architecture with memory protection on a microprocessor.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Prime, Stratus, Apollo, IBM System/38, and IBM AS/400 (including IBM i) computers use memory segmentation.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Burroughs introduced segmentation on the B5000, followed by the compatible B5500 and B5700.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The later B6500 replaced the Program Reference Table (PRT) with a Saguaro stack, changed control word formats, changed descriptor formats and changed the mechanism for referring to a control word or descriptor.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Descriptors have the uppermost bit set in the word.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] They reside in either the Program Reference Table (PRT) or the stack, and contain a *presence bit* indicating whether the data are present in memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] There are distinct data and program descriptors.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Words in the B6500 and its successors have 48 bits of data and 3 tag bits.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The tag bits indicate the type of data contained in the word; there are several descriptor types, indicated by different tag bit values.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Control words and descriptors reside in the Saguaro stack.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The line includes the B6500, B6700, B7700, B6800, B6900, B5900, the A-series Burroughs and Unisys machines, and the current Clearpath MCP systems (Libra).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] While there have been a few enhancements over the years, particularly hardware advances, the architecture has changed little.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The segmentation scheme has remained the same, see Segmented memory.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Each segment table entry contains a page table location, a page table length and an invalid bit.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Each of IBM's DAT implementations includes a translation cache, which IBM called a Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] While Principles of Operation discusses the TLB in general terms, the details are not part of the architecture and vary from model to model.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] DAS supports a translation table to convert a 16-bit address space number (ASN) to an STD, with privileged instructions to load the STD into CR1 (primary) or CR7 (secondary).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] (Optional expanded memory hardware can add bank-switched memory under software control.) Intel retroactively named the sole operating mode of these x86 CPU models "real mode".
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The Intel 80286 and later processors add "286 protected mode", which retains 16-bit addressing, and adds segmentation (without paging) and per-segment memory protection.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] For backward compatibility, all x86 CPUs start up in "real mode", with the same fixed overlapping 64 KiB segments, no memory protection, only 1 MiB physical address space, and some subtle differences (high memory area, unreal mode).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] In order to use its full 24-bit (16 MiB) physical address space and advanced MMU features, an 80286 or later processor must be switched into "protected mode" by software, usually the operating system or a DOS extender.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] If a program does not use the segment registers, or only puts values into them that it receives from the operating system, then identical code can run in real mode or protected mode, but most real-mode software computes new values for the segment registers, breaking this compatibility.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The Intel i386 and later processors add "386 protected mode", which uses 32-bit addressing, retains segmentation, and adds memory paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] In these processors, the segment table, rather than pointing to a page table for the segment, contains the segment address in *linear memory*.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] When paging is enabled, addresses in linear memory are then mapped to physical addresses using a separate page table.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Most operating systems did not use the segmentation capability, opting to keep the base address in all segment registers equal to 0 at all times and provide per-page memory protection and swapping using only paging.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Some use the CS register to provide executable-space protection on processors lacking the NX bit or use the FS or GS registers to access thread-local storage.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The x86-64 architecture does not support segmentation in "long mode" (64-bit mode).
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] Four of the segment registers: CS, SS, DS, and ES are forced to 0, and the limit to 264.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] The segment registers FS and GS can still have a nonzero base address.
[src:memory-protection-unit/memory-segmentation] This allows operating systems to use these segments for special purposes such as thread-local storage.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In computer science, **hierarchical protection domains**, often called **protection rings**, are mechanisms to protect data and functionality from faults (by improving fault tolerance) and malicious behavior (by providing computer security).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Computer operating systems provide different levels of access to resources.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] A protection ring is one of two or more hierarchical *levels* or *layers* of privilege within the architecture of a computer system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] This is generally hardware-enforced by some CPU architectures that provide different CPU modes at the hardware or microcode level.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Rings are arranged in a hierarchy from most privileged (most trusted, usually numbered zero) to least privileged (least trusted, usually with the highest ring number).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] On most operating systems, Ring 0 is the level with the most privileges and interacts most directly with the physical hardware such as certain CPU functionality (e.g. the control registers) and I/O controllers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Special mechanisms are provided to allow an outer ring to access an inner ring's resources in a predefined manner, as opposed to allowing arbitrary usage.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Correctly gating access between rings can improve security by preventing programs from one ring or privilege level from misusing resources intended for programs in another.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] For example, spyware running as a user program in Ring 3 should be prevented from turning on a web camera without informing the user, since hardware access should be a Ring 1 function reserved for device drivers.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Programs such as web browsers running in higher numbered rings must request access to the network, a resource restricted to a lower numbered ring.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] X86S, a canceled Intel architecture published in 2024, has only ring 0 and ring 3.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Ring 1 and 2 were to be removed under X86S since modern operating systems never utilize them.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Multiple rings of protection were among the most revolutionary concepts introduced by the Multics operating system, a highly secure predecessor of today's Unix family of operating systems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] However, most general-purpose systems use only two rings, even if the hardware they run on provides more CPU modes than that.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] For example, Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 (and their predecessors) use only two rings, with ring 0 corresponding to kernel mode and ring 3 to user mode, because earlier versions of Windows NT ran on processors that supported only two protection levels.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Many modern CPU architectures (including the popular Intel x86 architecture) include some form of ring protection, although the Windows NT operating system, like Unix, does not fully utilize this feature.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] OS/2 does, to some extent, use three rings: ring 0 for kernel code and device drivers, ring 2 for privileged code (user programs with I/O access permissions), and ring 3 for unprivileged code (nearly all user programs).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Under DOS, the kernel, drivers and applications typically run on ring 3 (however, this is exclusive to the case where protected-mode drivers or DOS extenders are used; as a real-mode OS, the system runs with effectively no protection), whereas 386 memory managers such as EMM386 run at ring 0.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In addition to this, DR-DOS' EMM386 3.xx can optionally run some modules (such as DPMS) on ring 1 instead.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] OpenVMS uses four modes called (in order of decreasing privileges) Kernel, Executive, Supervisor and User.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The original Multics system had eight rings, but many modern systems have fewer.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The hardware remains aware of the current ring of the executing instruction thread at all times, with the help of a special machine register.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In some systems, areas of virtual memory are instead assigned ring numbers in hardware.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] One example is the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, in which the top three bits of the program counter (PC) served as the ring register.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Thus code executing with the virtual PC set to 0xE200000, for example, would automatically be in ring 7, and calling a subroutine in a different section of memory would automatically cause a ring transfer.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The hardware severely restricts the ways in which control can be passed from one ring to another, and also enforces restrictions on the types of memory access that can be performed across rings.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The hardware restrictions are designed to limit opportunities for accidental or malicious breaches of security.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In addition, the most privileged ring may be given special capabilities (such as real memory addressing that bypasses the virtual memory hardware).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] ARM version 7 architecture implements three privilege levels: application (PL0), operating system (PL1), and hypervisor (PL2).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Unusually, level 0 (PL0) is the least-privileged level, while level 2 is the most-privileged level.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] ARM version 8 implements four exception levels: application (EL0), operating system (EL1), hypervisor (EL2), and secure monitor / firmware (EL3), for AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Ring protection can be combined with processor modes (master/kernel/privileged/supervisor mode versus slave/unprivileged/user mode) in some systems.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Operating systems running on hardware supporting both may use both forms of protection or only one.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Effective use of ring architecture requires close cooperation between hardware and the operating system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Operating systems designed to work on multiple hardware platforms may make only limited use of rings if they are not present on every supported platform.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Often the security model is simplified to "kernel" and "user" even if hardware provides finer granularity through rings.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In computer terms, *supervisor mode* is a hardware-mediated flag that can be changed by code running in system-level software.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] System-level tasks or threads may have this flag set while they are running, whereas user-level applications will not.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] This flag determines whether it would be possible to execute machine code operations such as modifying registers for various descriptor tables, or performing operations such as disabling interrupts.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The idea of having two different modes to operate in comes from "with more power comes more responsibility" – a program in supervisor mode is trusted never to fail, since a failure may cause the whole computer system to crash.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Supervisor mode is "an execution mode on some processors which enables execution of all instructions, including privileged instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] It may also give access to a different address space, to memory management hardware and to other peripherals.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In a monolithic kernel, the operating system runs in supervisor mode and the applications run in user mode.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Other types of operating systems, like those with an exokernel or microkernel, do not necessarily share this behavior.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Most processors have at least two different modes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The x86-processors have four different modes divided into four different rings.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Programs that run in Ring 0 can do *anything* with the system, and code that runs in Ring 3 should be able to fail at any time without impact to the rest of the computer system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Ring 1 and Ring 2 are rarely used, but could be configured with different levels of access.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In most existing systems, switching from user mode to kernel mode has an associated high cost in performance.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] It has been measured, on the basic request `getpid`, to cost 1000–1500 cycles on most machines.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Of these just around 100 are for the actual switch (70 from user to kernel space, and 40 back), the rest is "kernel overhead".
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In the L3 microkernel, the minimization of this overhead reduced the overall cost to around 150 cycles.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] To gain performance and determinism, some systems place functions that would likely be viewed as application logic, rather than as device drivers, in kernel mode; security applications (access control, firewalls, etc.) and operating system monitors are cited as examples.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Functions are also sometimes moved across rings in the other direction.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The Linux kernel, for instance, injects into processes a vDSO section which contains functions that would normally require a system call, i.e. a ring transition.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Instead of doing a syscall these functions use static data provided by the kernel.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] This avoids the need for a ring transition and so is more lightweight than a syscall.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The function gettimeofday can be provided this way.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Recent CPUs from Intel and AMD offer x86 virtualization instructions for a hypervisor to control Ring 0 hardware access.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Although they are mutually incompatible, both Intel VT-x (codenamed "Vanderpool") and AMD-V (codenamed "Pacifica") allow a guest operating system to run Ring 0 operations natively without affecting other guests or the host OS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Before hardware-assisted virtualization, guest operating systems ran under ring 1.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Any attempt that requires a higher privilege level to perform (ring 0) will produce an interrupt and then be handled using software; this is called "Trap and Emulate".
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] To assist virtualization and reduce overhead caused by the reason above, VT-x and AMD-V allow the guest to run under Ring 0.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] VT-x introduces VMX Root/Non-root Operation: The hypervisor runs in VMX Root Operation mode, possessing the highest privilege.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Guest OS runs in VMX Non-Root Operation mode, which allows them to operate at ring 0 without having actual hardware privileges.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] VMX non-root operation and VMX transitions are controlled by a data structure called a virtual-machine control.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] These hardware extensions allow classical "Trap and Emulate" virtualization to perform on x86 architecture but now with hardware support.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] A **privilege level** in the x86 instruction set controls the access of the program currently running on the processor to resources such as memory regions, I/O ports, and special instructions.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] There are 4 privilege levels ranging from 0 which is the most privileged, to 3 which is least privileged.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Most modern operating systems use level 0 for the kernel/executive, and use level 3 for application programs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Any resource available to level n is also available to levels 0 to n, so the privilege levels are rings.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] When a lesser privileged process tries to access a higher privileged process, a general protection fault exception is reported to the OS.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] It is not necessary to use all four privilege levels.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Current operating systems with wide market share including Microsoft Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS and Android mostly use a paging mechanism with only one bit to specify the privilege level as either Supervisor or User (U/S Bit).
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Code running in real mode is executed at level 0 (highest privilege level) whereas code running in virtual-8086 mode is executed at level 3.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Potential future uses for the multiple privilege levels supported by the x86 ISA family include containerization and virtual machines.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] A host operating system kernel could use instructions with full privilege access (kernel mode), whereas applications running on the guest OS in a virtual machine or container could use the lowest level of privileges in user mode.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The virtual machine and guest OS kernel could themselves use an intermediate level of instruction privilege to invoke and virtualize kernel-mode operations such as system calls from the point of view of the guest operating system.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The **IOPL** (**I/O Privilege level**) flag is a flag found on all IA-32 compatible x86 CPUs.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] It occupies bits 12 and 13 in the FLAGS register.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In protected mode and long mode, it shows the I/O privilege level of the current program or task.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The Current Privilege Level (CPL) (CPL0, CPL1, CPL2, CPL3) of the task or program must be less than or equal to the IOPL in order for the task or program to access I/O ports.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] The IOPL can be changed using `POPF(D)` and `IRET(D)` only when the current privilege level is Ring 0.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Besides IOPL, the I/O Port Permissions in the TSS also take part in determining the ability of a task to access an I/O port.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] In x86 systems, the x86 hardware virtualization (VT-x and SVM) is referred as "ring −1", the System Management Mode is referred as "ring −2", the Intel Management Engine and AMD Platform Security Processor are sometimes referred as "ring −3".
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Many CPU hardware architectures provide far more flexibility than is exploited by the operating systems that they normally run.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Proper use of complex CPU modes requires very close cooperation between the operating system and the CPU, and thus tends to tie the OS to the CPU architecture.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] For example, the reason Windows uses only two levels (ring 0 and ring 3) is that some hardware architectures that were supported in the past (such as PowerPC or MIPS) implemented only two privilege levels.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Multics was an operating system designed specifically for a special CPU architecture (which in turn was designed specifically for Multics), and it took full advantage of the CPU modes available to it.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] However, it was an exception to the rule.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Today, this high degree of interoperation between the OS and the hardware is not often cost-effective, despite the potential advantages for security and stability.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Ultimately, the purpose of distinct operating modes for the CPU is to provide hardware protection against accidental or deliberate corruption of the system environment (and corresponding breaches of system security) by software.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Only "trusted" portions of system software are allowed to execute in the unrestricted environment of kernel mode, and then, in paradigmatic designs, only when absolutely necessary.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] All other software executes in one or more user modes.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] If a processor generates a fault or exception condition in a user mode, in most cases system stability is unaffected; if a processor generates a fault or exception condition in kernel mode, most operating systems will halt the system with an unrecoverable error.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] When a hierarchy of modes exists (ring-based security), faults and exceptions at one privilege level may destabilize only the higher-numbered privilege levels.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Thus, a fault in Ring 0 (the kernel mode with the highest privilege) will crash the entire system, but a fault in Ring 2 will only affect Rings 3 and beyond and Ring 2 itself, at most.
[src:memory-protection-unit/protection-ring] Microkernel operating systems attempt to minimize the amount of code running in privileged mode, for purposes of security and elegance.
